 States Representative for [[New York's 4th congressional district]]. She is a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]].\n\nPrior to serving in Congress, she served as the [[Nassau County, New York|Nassau County]] District Attorney, and, prior to that, she served as a federal prosecutor in the U.S. Attorney's Office in [[Philadelphia]] and as an assistant district attorney in the [[Brooklyn|Kings County]] District Attorney's Office in [[New York City]].\n\nRice announced on January 29, 2014 that she would run for Congress in 2014 in New York's 4th congressional district to replace retiring Democratic incumbent [[Carolyn McCarthy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/nassau/kathleen-rice-to-seek-carolyn-mccarthy-seat-in-congress-1.6905396|title=Kathleen Rice to seek Carolyn McCarthy seat in Congress|author=PAUL LAROCCO|date=January 30, 2014|work=Newsday}}</ref> Rice won the election over Republican Bruce Blakeman on November 4, 2014<ref>\"[https://www.elections.ny.gov/2014ElectionResults.html 2014 Election Results]\". New York State Board of Elections. See: \"[https://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2014/general/2014Congress.xlsx Representative in Congress]\", section: 4th Congressional District. Retrieved 2017-01-24.</ref> and took office in January 2015.\n\n==Early life, education, and career==\nRice was born in [[Manhattan]], [[New York (state)|New York]] to Laurence and Christine Rice. She grew up in [[Garden City, New York|Garden City]], on [[Long Island]], as one of 10 siblings. Rice graduated from [[Garden City High School (New York)|Garden City High School]]. She received a B.A. degree from the [[The Catholic University of America|Catholic University]] in 1987 and a J.D. degree from the [[Touro Law Center]] in 1991.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Nassau County Democrats. nassaucountydems.com|url=http://nassaucountydems.com/officeholder/kathleen-rice|title=Kathleen Rice|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029193237/http://nassaucountydems.com/officeholder/kathleen-rice|archive-date=October 29, 2013|access-date=2017-01-24}}</ref>\n\nRice began her career as an assistant district attorney in the [[Brooklyn|Kings County]] District Attorney's Office, under District Attorney [[Charles Hynes]] in 1992. She prosecuted cases involving burglaries, robberies and sexual assaults and was the first member of her class to be promoted to the homicide bureau.<ref name=\"Touro\">{{cite web|publisher=Touro Law Center|url=https://www.tourolaw.edu/alumni/alumniDetail.aspx?id=57|title=Alumni of the Month Program: Kathleen Rice|date=May 2008|access-date=2017-01-24}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Rice was appointed assistant [[United States Attorney]] in [[Philadelphia]] by then-[[Attorney General]] [[Janet Reno]]. As a federal prosecutor, she prosecuted white-collar crimes, corporate fraud, gun and drug cases, and public corruption.<ref name=\"Touro\"/>\n\n==Nassau County District Attorney==\nRice was elected Nassau County District Attorney in 2005, winning by 7,500 votes to become the first female to hold the position. She defeated 31-year incumbent [[Denis Dillon]], who had generally won reelection easily, even after switching his affiliation from Democratic to Republican in 1989.  Rice was the first serious opponent that Dillon had faced since his first run in 1974.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=362305|title=Our Campaigns - Nassau County District Attorney Race - Nov 08, 2005|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nRice was re-elected in 2009 and 2013.\n\n===Tenure and issues===\n\n;Drunken and drugged driving\n\nIn 2006, Rice, the \"state's toughest DWI prosecutor,\"<ref>{{cite web|work=New York Daily News|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/nassau-county-district-attorney-rice-joins-fight-leandra-law-article-1.414538|title=Nassau County District Attorney Rice joins fight for 'Leandra's Law'|date=November 14, 2009}}</ref> declared her first major policy initiative to be an \"assault on the drunk driving epidemic.\" She lowered the blood-alcohol level at which you could take a plea bargain,<ref>{{cite web|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/14/nyregion/14drunk.html?pagewanted=print|title=A Harder Line on Driving While Drunk|date=March 14, 2006}}</ref> supported Leandra's Law, and charged with murder some drunk drivers who killed their victims.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|work=New York Daily News|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/boroughs/new-da-town-hillary-swear-kathleen-rice-nassau-article-1.635672|title=A NEW DA IN TOWN Hillary to swear in Kathleen Rice in Nassau|date=January 8, 2006}}</ref>\n \n;Reform efforts\n\nIn September 2011, Rice's office arrested seven students after uncovering an [[SAT]] cheating ring on Long Island.<ref>{{cite web|work=ABC News|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/sat-cheating-ring-busted-york-students-arrested/story?id=14617306|title=SAT Cheating Ring Busted, Seven Students Arrested|date=September 27, 2011}}</ref> When this case led to the discovery of a wider-spread cheating scandal, Rice worked with the [[College Board]], who administers the test, to update security standards to halt cheating in the future. This effort sparked other test administrators, like that which gives the [[ACT (test)|ACT]], to update their standards as well.<ref>{{cite web|work=ABC News|url=http://abcnews.go.com/News/BacktoSchool/sat-security-ny-cheating-ring/story?id=16012528|title=New SAT Security Changes After N.Y. Cheating Ring|date=March 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nRice has also received credit for teen education programs geared towards cyber bullying, drug use, texting and dangerous driving.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hackmack |first=Andrew |date=May 30, 2012 |url=http://www.liherald.com/stories/District-attorney-highlights-crime-prevention-initiatives,41177 |title=District attorney highlights crime prevention initiatives: Rice speaks to Valley Stream business leaders |website=LIHerald.com |accessdate=2017-01-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=Nassau County District Attorney|url=http://www.nassaucountyny.gov/agencies/da/heroineawareness.html|title=Heroin Prevention PSA|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029185809/http://www.nassaucountyny.gov/agencies/da/heroineawareness.html|archivedate=October 29, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=Anton News|url=http://www.antonnews.com/massapequanobserver/news/6347-dwi-education-program-at-local-schools.html|title=DWI Education Program at Local Schools|date=February 26, 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923200922/http://www.antonnews.com/massapequanobserver/news/6347-dwi-education-program-at-local-schools.html|archivedate=September 23, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=FiOs1|url=http://www.fios1news.com/longisland/longisland/node/38822?quicktabs_1=0#.UmmufhaChUR|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029184748/http://www.fios1news.com/longisland/longisland/node/38822?quicktabs_1=0|dead-url=yes|archive-date=October 29, 2013|title=Nassau County DA Attacks Cyber Crime [video]|date=July 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Rice's office, Nassau County and [[Hempstead (village), New York|Hempstead]] police led a counter-assault on Terrace Avenue, a major drug haven and crime-ridden street in [[Long Island]]'s Hempstead Village. Through a combination of zero-tolerance enforcement for repeat and violent offenders, and social-service based jail diversion for nonviolent and first time offenders, crime has been reduced in the area.<ref>{{cite web|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/18/nyregion/long-island/18terraceli.html?_r=0|title=Street Known for Drug Crime Is Getting Clean|date=January 14, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, following the trampling death of a [[Walmart]] employee at one of the retailer's Black Friday sales events, Rice encouraged Walmart to upgrade its security protocols at its nearly 100 New York stores.<ref>{{cite web|work=USA Today|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/industries/retail/2009-05-06-walmart-death_N.htm|title=Wal-Mart pays $2M to avoid charges in death probe|date=May 6, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Rice came out in favor of decriminalizing small amounts of \"plain view\" marijuana.<ref>{{cite web|work=The Village Voice|url=http://blogs.villagevoice.com/runninscared/2012/06/cuomos_plan_to.php|title=Cuomo's Plan To Decriminalize Weed In \"Public View\" Has Support Of Pretty Much Everyone|date=June 4, 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029185733/http://blogs.villagevoice.com/runninscared/2012/06/cuomos_plan_to.php|archivedate=October 29, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Rice has also supported efforts to allow some citizens to seal prior low-level, non-violent convictions in the hopes of improving their chances of obtaining employment.<ref>{{cite web|work=Newsday|url=http://www.pfa-li.com/sealrecs.html|title=Debate over sealing records on old crimes|date=June 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\nRice was chosen by Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] to be a member of the Moreland Commission on Utility Storm Preparation and Response, a panel tasked with investigating the failures of the [[Long Island Power Authority]] (LIPA) following Hurricane Sandy of October 2012. The panel recommended that LIPA be replaced by a private, investor-owned company and that the Public Service Commission, which has regulation authority, be given more power to penalize and fine poor-performing utility companies.\n\nRice supports the \"Raise the Age NY\" initiative to treat non-violent teen offenders as juveniles in the criminal justice system.<ref>{{cite web|work=Newsday|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/nassau/advocates-to-state-don-t-prosecute-16-17-year-olds-as-adults-1.5923709|title=Advocates to state: Don't prosecute 16-, 17-year olds as adults|date=August 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n;Guns, gangs, and violent crime\n[[File:Arrests in Ticket Vending Machine Scam (10614601376).jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|Kathleen Rice at a press conference, announcing the arrest of four ticket vending machine scammers (2013)]]\nRice implemented gun buy-back programs in some of the county's most crime-plagued areas, which removed more than 2,000 guns from the streets.<ref>\"[http://archive.nassaucountyny.gov/agencies/DA/NewsReleases/2013/013013buyback.html DA Rice and County Executive Mangano Announce Gun Buyback Event]\" [news release]. Nassau County, NY official website. January 30, 2013. The statistic for number of guns taken off the streets is cited by Nassau County executive Edward Mangano. Retrieved 2015-06-26.</ref> She also spoke out in favor of Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]]'s gun control legislation,<ref>{{cite web|work=The Albany Times-Union|url=http://blog.timesunion.com/guns/top-law-enforcement-officials-file-in-support-of-safe-act/2124/|title=Top law enforcement officials file in support of SAFE Act|date=June 25, 2013}}</ref> and she created the office's first ever gun prosecution unit.<ref>{{cite web|work=Kathleen Rice Campaign Website|url=http://www.kathleenrice.com/record/2012-08-a-new-approach-to-gangs--guns|title=A New Approach to Gangs & Guns|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029190616/http://www.kathleenrice.com/record/2012-08-a-new-approach-to-gangs--guns|archivedate=October 29, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\nRice announced in early 2011 a major prosecution of 9 gun dealers and gun store employees arrested by police in an undercover operation investigating alleged illegal assault weapons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abclocal.go.com/story?section=news/local/long_island&id=7965139|title=Nassau County undercover illegal gun bust makes nine arrests - null|date=February 17, 2011|publisher=|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029111447/http://abclocal.go.com/story?section=news%2Flocal%2Flong_island&id=7965139|archivedate=October 29, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> This was the second arrest for Martin Tretola, one of the gunshop owners.  He was previously arrested on firearms related violations in 2007.  Subsequently, in 2012, a federal jury delivered a verdict rejecting the charges of Nassau County and District Attorney Rice for the 2007 arrest and awarded Tretola 3 million dollars in compensatory damages and 2 million dollars in punitive damages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theislandnow.com/williston_park/news/article_d76d95ee-ed56-11e1-92b0-001a4bcf887a.html|title=GCP gun store owner awarded $5M|work=The Island Now|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303033432/http://www.theislandnow.com/williston_park/news/article_d76d95ee-ed56-11e1-92b0-001a4bcf887a.html|archivedate=March 3, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> This judgment was later reduced to 1.3 million dollars in total upon appeal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsnyork.com/seaford-gun-shop-owner-gets-1-3m-judgment-from-nassau-in-wrongful-arrest-case/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-29 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20141029072526/http://newsnyork.com/seaford-gun-shop-owner-gets-1-3m-judgment-from-nassau-in-wrongful-arrest-case/ |archivedate=October 29, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n'''Questions on Rice's early prosecution cases'''\n\nThe Kings County district attorney's prosecution of Antowine Butts for double homicide imploded and ended in an acquittal in 2000, but not before Butts spent two years in a Rikers Island jail cell. After the case unraveled, Butts alleged that he was a victim of prosecutorial misconduct in a civil rights lawsuit that was settled with New York City.\n\nAmong those named in that suit: Kathleen Rice, the architect of the case against Butts.\nDespite that high profile, Rice has largely escaped attention \u2014 including during the current campaign \u2014 for starting her career in an office in which prosecutors are alleged to have put some innocent people behind bars with coerced confessions, bogus witness statements, coached lineup identifications and other tactics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.newsday.com/projects/long-island/questions-rices-early-prosecution-cases/|title=Questions on Rice's early prosecution cases - Newsday|work=Newsday}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, Rice announced the arrest of 18 members of the \"Rollin' 60's\" gang, an \"ultra-violent\" subset of the Crips. Rice charged these defendants with crimes ranging from attempted murder of a police officer, to assault and robbery, to gun and drug sales.<ref>{{cite web|work=Newsday|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/nassau/nassau-officials-ultra-violent-gang-members-arrested-1.5096256|title=Nassau officials: 'Ultra-violent' gang members arrested|date=April 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n;Public corruption\nAmong those Rice has charged and convicted of corruption include a deputy police commissioner,<ref>{{cite web|work=The Long Island Press|url=http://www.longislandpress.com/2013/02/14/nassau-police-conspiracy-partial-verdict-flanagan-guilty-of-official-misconduct/|title=Nassau Police Conspiracy Partial Verdict: Flanagan Guilty of Official Misconduct|date=February 14, 2013}}</ref> a [[Long Beach, New York|Long Beach]] City Council member,<ref>{{cite web|work=Newsday|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/towns/jury-long-beach-city-councilman-michael-fagen-guilty-of-larceny-1.4567661|title=Jury: Long Beach City Councilman Michael Fagen guilty of larceny|date=February 5, 2013}}</ref> former [[Nassau County, New York|Nassau County]] legislators,<ref>{{cite web|work=Long Island Herald|url=http://www.liherald.com/westhempstead/stories/Roger-Corbin-found-guilty-of-taking-bribes,42272|title=Roger Corbin found guilty of taking bribes|date=July 24, 2012}}</ref> and several town building department employees.<ref>{{cite web|work=Anton News|url=http://www.antonnews.com/manhassetpress/2007/10/19/news/buildingdept.html|title=Indictments Handed Down in  TNH Building Department Probe|date=October 19, 2007|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029195919/http://www.antonnews.com/manhassetpress/2007/10/19/news/buildingdept.html|archivedate=October 29, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kathleen Rice.jpg|thumb|150px|Rice in 2013]]\nIn July 2013, Kathleen Rice was appointed by Governor Cuomo to be one of three co-chairs of the Moreland Commission on Public Corruption. The work of the commission is currently ongoing.<ref>{{cite web|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/03/nyregion/cuomo-names-panel-to-investigate-corrupt-elected-officials.html?_r=0|title=Cuomo Creates Special Commission to Investigate Corrupt Elected Officials|date=July 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nRice formed Nassau's first-ever [[Medicaid]] and public assistance fraud unit, which has since secured millions of dollars in restitution for Nassau taxpayers.<ref>{{cite web|work=Kathleen Rice Campaign Website|url=http://www.kathleenrice.com/record/2012-08-protecting-taxpayer-dollars|title=Protecting Taxpayer Dollars|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023234604/http://www.kathleenrice.com/record/2012-08-protecting-taxpayer-dollars|archivedate=October 23, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;DA's Office gender pay gap and part-time employees\nRice has reformed the recruiting, hiring and promotional practices of her office. She eliminated a gender pay gap that had previously been greater than 30%. Rice developed an aimed at offering flex-and part-time work schedules to those needing to care for a family member or a personal situation. Half of the attorneys and management in Rice's office are women.<ref>{{cite web|work=Kathleen Rice Campaign Website|url=http://www.kathleenrice.com/record/2012-08-promoting-equality-in-the-workplace|title=Promoting Equality in the Workplace|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029193637/http://www.kathleenrice.com/record/2012-08-promoting-equality-in-the-workplace|archivedate=October 29, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Jesse Friedman case\nIn 2010, Rice ordered the review of a 1987 case in which Arnold Friedman and his son, Jesse, pleaded guilty to sexually abusing young boys in their Great Neck, Long Island home. Rice formed a panel of outside experts \u2013 including the [[Innocence Project]]'s [[Barry Scheck]] \u2013 to examine whether or not Jesse Friedman had wrongfully confessed. In a 172-page report released in July 2013, investigators found that Friedman had not been wrongfully convicted.<ref>{{cite web|work=New York Daily News|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/jesse-friedman-100-guilty-child-abuse-article-1.1380786|title=Jesse Friedman is 100% guilty of sexually abusing children, reinvestigation by Nassau County district attorney concludes|date=June 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==2010 Attorney General campaign==\nIn May 2010, Rice announced that she would seek the Democratic nomination for [[New York State Attorney General]]. The race pitted Rice against four Democratic opponents: then-State Senator [[Eric Schneiderman]], former prosecutor [[Sean Coffey]], former State Assemblyman [[Richard Brodsky]], and former insurance commissioner [[Eric Dinallo]]. Though originally considered a long shot, Rice would narrowly lose the five-way primary to Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, 34% to 32%.<ref>{{cite web|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/15/nyregion/15nyag.html|title=Schneiderman Wins Democratic Attorney General Race|date=September 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==President of DAASNY==\nIn July 2013, Rice was inducted as President of the [[District Attorneys Association of the State of New York]] (DAASNY).<ref>{{cite web|work=Newsday|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/nassau/kathleen-rice-to-lead-state-district-attorneys-1.5753929|title=Kathleen Rice to lead state district attorneys|date=July 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===2014 election===\nIn June, 2014, Rice won the Democratic primary election for U.S. House of Representatives in New York's fourth congressional district, defeating Nassau County Legislator Kevan Abrahams 56%-44%.<ref>{{cite news|last1=LaRocco|first1=Paul|title=Rice, Blakeman win 4th district primaries|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/nassau/low-turnout-in-4th-district-congressional-primaries-1.8556966|accessdate=2014-11-10|agency=Newsday|date=2014-06-25}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, Rice was elected to the U.S. House of Representatives in New York's fourth congressional district, defeating Republican candidate Bruce Blakeman 53%-47%.<ref name=\"2014election\">{{cite web|last1=Nassau County Board of Elections|title=2014 General Election Results|url=http://www.nassaucountyny.gov/agencies/boe/results.html|website=Nassau County Board of Elections|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218140802/http://www.nassaucountyny.gov/agencies/boe/results.html|archive-date=February 18, 2015|accessdate=2017-01-24}}</ref>\n\n===2016 election===\nRice won reelection in 2016 against Republican David Gurfein, 59.6%-40.4%, with a margin of about 60,000 votes.<ref name=\"2016election\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/new-york-house-district-4-rice-gurfein |title=New York U.S. House 4th District Results: Kathleen Rice Wins |work=The New York Times |access-date=2017-10-18 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|Committee on Homeland Security]]'''\n**[[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response, and Communications|Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response, and Communications]]\n**[[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Transportation Security|Subcommittee on Transportation Security]] (Ranking Member)\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Veterans' Affairs|Committee on Veterans' Affairs]]'''\n**[[United States House Veterans' Affairs Subcommittee on Economic Opportunity|Subcommittee on Economic Opportunity]]\n**[[United States House Veterans' Affairs Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n*'''[[New Democrat Coalition]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://newdemocratcoalition-himes.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=New Democrat Coalition|date=|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n\n===2005 election===\nIn 2005, Kathleen Rice returned home to Nassau County and declared her candidacy for [[District Attorney]] on the Democratic line. Rice challenged 30-year incumbent DA [[Denis Dillon]]. Throughout the campaign, Rice provided an alternative to Dillon, pledging to cut plea bargaining and touting her would-be zero tolerance policy for drunk driving. Rice also committed herself to modernizing the office's approach to domestic violence and crimes of sexual abuse. Rice edged out Dillon 51%\u201349% in the November election.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===2009 re-election===\nIn 2009, Rice was challenged by Law Clerk Joy Watson. Rice defeated Watson 54%\u201346%.\n\n===2010 Attorney General Democratic Primary===\nIn 2010, Rice ran for Attorney General of the State of New York in the Democratic Primary.\n\n===2013 re-election===\nIn 2013, Rice was challenged by Law Secretary Howard Sturim. Rice defeated Sturim 59%\u201341%.\n\n===Election results===\n{{Election box begin no change| title=2005 Nassau County District Attorney General Election<ref>{{cite web|work=Nassau GOP Watch|url=http://nassaugopwatch.blogspot.com/2005/11/democrats-hold-nassau-and-take-da.html|title=2005 Nassau Election Results|date=November 9, 2005}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n|party = Democratic Party (United States)\n|candidate = '''Kathleen Rice'''\n| votes = '''151,819'''\n|percentage = 51.35\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n|party = Republican Party (United States)\n|candidate = Denis Dillon (incumbent)\n| votes = '''143,827'''\n|percentage = 48.65\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 295,646\n| percentage= 100}}\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change| title=2009 Nassau Count